AB  - Eventually, the ways of interactions among humans, health devices, and healthcare facilities are evolving and becoming smarter and quicker. Wireless wearables unified with IoT are becoming an effective everyday tool to analyze and collect patients' health data and keep a track of the health of those who have a risk of persistent disease. Uninterrupted attendance by the healthcare workers and convenience for the patients during a crisis in remote areas is the primary factor to be addressed by a healthcare monitoring system. Such a system materializes personal medical treatment to rural patients and helps to reduce their medical costs with a constantly enhanced outcome. LoRa due to its wide coverage, offers a concrete framework for IoT that can certainly transform the healthcare trade to the next level yet it encounters some challenges like latency, unbalanced loading of data, and diverseness of the applications and user requests. Healthcare is such a field where even a little delay may cost the life of a patient. Cloud computing has been considered as a base to provide IoT solutions but it too calls for limitations when it comes to distance from the point of origin of IoT data. There is an upsurge of Fog computing solutions, to eradicate such challenges by bringing computation power nearer to the origin of data. Notwithstanding, the cloud-fog-IoT unification and interoperability entail intricate engineering of services and applications so that the solutions can utilize the distributed resources without bargaining the Quality of Service (QoS), privacy, and efficiency.  © 2023 IEEE.
